# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: miller-rabin-primality
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The algorithm was the first one which is able to determine in polynomial time, whether a given number is prime or composite without relying on mathematical conjectures such as the generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The proof is also notable for not relying on the field of analysis.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] In 2006 the authors received both the Gödel Prize and Fulkerson Prize for their work.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] AKS is the first primality-proving algorithm to be simultaneously *general*, *polynomial-time*, *deterministic*, and *unconditionally correct*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Previous algorithms had been developed for centuries and achieved three of these properties at most, but not all four.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] While the algorithm is of immense theoretical importance, it is not used in practice, rendering it a galactic algorithm.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] For 64-bit inputs, the Baillie–PSW test is deterministic and runs many orders of magnitude faster.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] For larger inputs, the performance of the (also unconditionally correct) ECPP and APR tests is *far* superior to AKS.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Additionally, ECPP can output a primality certificate that allows independent and rapid verification of the results, which is not possible with the AKS algorithm.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] holds within the polynomial ring $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} )[X]$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Note that X denotes the indeterminate which generates this polynomial ring.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] This theorem is a generalization to polynomials of Fermat's little theorem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] While the relation (**1**) constitutes a primality test in itself, verifying it takes exponential time: the brute force approach would require the expansion of the $(X+a)^{n}$ polynomial and a reduction ${\pmod {n}}$ of the resulting $n+1$ coefficients.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The congruence is an equality in the polynomial ring $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} )[X]$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Evaluating in a quotient ring of $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} )[X]$ creates an upper bound for the degree of the polynomials involved.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The AKS evaluates the equality in $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} )[X]/(X^{r}-1)$ , making the computational complexity dependent on the size of r .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Note that all primes satisfy this relation (choosing $g=0$ in (**3**) gives (**1**), which holds for n prime).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] This congruence can be checked in polynomial time when r is polynomial to the digits of n .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The AKS algorithm evaluates this congruence for a large set of a values, whose size is polynomial to the digits of n .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The proof of validity of the AKS algorithm shows that one can find an r and a set of a values with the above properties such that if the congruences hold then n is a power of a prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] In the first version of the above-cited paper, the authors proved the asymptotic time complexity of the algorithm to be ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{12})$ (using Õ from big O notation)—the twelfth power of the number of digits in *n* times a factor that is polylogarithmic in the number of digits.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] However, this upper bound was rather loose; a widely-held conjecture about the distribution of the Sophie Germain primes would, if true, immediately cut the worst case down to ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{6})$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] In the months following the discovery, new variants appeared (Lenstra 2002, Pomerance 2002, Berrizbeitia 2002, Cheng 2003, Bernstein 2003a/b, Lenstra and Pomerance 2003), which improved the speed of computation greatly.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Owing to the existence of the many variants, Crandall and Papadopoulos refer to the "AKS-class" of algorithms in their scientific paper "On the implementation of AKS-class primality tests", published in March 2003.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] In response to some of these variants, and to other feedback, the paper "PRIMES is in P" was updated with a new formulation of the AKS algorithm and of its proof of correctness.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] (This version was eventually published in *Annals of Mathematics*.) While the basic idea remained the same, *r* was chosen in a new manner, and the proof of correctness was more coherently organized.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The new proof relied almost exclusively on the behavior of cyclotomic polynomials over finite fields.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The new upper bound on time complexity was ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{10.5})$ , later reduced using additional results from sieve theory to ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{7.5})$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] In 2005, Pomerance and Lenstra demonstrated a variant of AKS that runs in ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{6})$ operations, leading to another updated version of the paper.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Agrawal, Kayal and Saxena proposed a variant which would run in ${\tilde {O}}(\log(n)^{3})$ if Agrawal's conjecture were true; however, a heuristic argument by Pomerance and Lenstra suggested that it is probably false.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Find the smallest *r* such that ord*r*(*n*) > (log2 *n*)2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] If *r* and *n* are not coprime, then output *composite*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Here ord*r*(*n*) is the multiplicative order of *n* modulo *r*, log2 is the binary logarithm, and $\varphi (r)$ is Euler's totient function of *r*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Step 3 is shown in the paper as checking 1 < gcd(*a*,*n*) < *n* for all *a* ≤ *r*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] It can be seen this is equivalent to trial division up to *r*, which can be done very efficiently without using gcd.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Once beyond very small inputs, step 5 dominates the time taken.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] This ring contains only the r monomials $\{X^{0},X^{1},\ldots ,X^{r-1}\}$ , and the coefficients are in $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ which has n elements, all of them codable within $\log _{2}(n)$ bits.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Most later improvements made to the algorithm have concentrated on reducing the size of *r,* which makes the core operation in step 5 faster, and in reducing the size of *s*, the number of loops performed in step 5.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Typically these changes do not change the computational complexity, but can lead to many orders of magnitude less time taken; for example, Bernstein's final version has a theoretical speedup by a factor of over 2 million.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] For the algorithm to be correct, all steps that identify *n* must be correct.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Steps 1, 3, and 4 are trivially correct, since they are based on direct tests of the divisibility of *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Step 5 is also correct: since (2) is true for any choice of *a* coprime to *n* and *r* if *n* is prime, an inequality means that *n* must be composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] The difficult part of the proof is showing that step 6 is true.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Its proof of correctness is based on the upper and lower bounds of a multiplicative group in $\mathbb {Z} _{n}[x]$ constructed from the (*X* + *a*) binomials that are tested in step 5.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Step 4 guarantees that these binomials are $\left\lfloor {\sqrt {\varphi (r)}}\log _{2}(n)\right\rfloor$ distinct elements of $\mathbb {Z} _{n}[x]$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] For the particular choice of *r*, the bounds produce a contradiction unless *n* is prime or a power of a prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Together with the test of step 1, this implies that *n* is always prime at step 6.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/aks-primality-test] Where PolynomialMod is a term-wise modulo reduction of the polynomial. e.g.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] for all integers b that are relatively prime to ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] They constitute the comparatively rare instances where the strict converse of Fermat's Little Theorem does not hold.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] This fact precludes the use of that theorem as an absolute test of primality.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The Carmichael numbers form the subset *K*1 of the Knödel numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The Carmichael numbers were named after the American mathematician Robert Carmichael by Nicolaas Beeger, in 1950. Øystein Ore had referred to them in 1948 as numbers with the "Fermat property", or "*F* numbers" for short.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Fermat's little theorem states that if p is a prime number, then for any integer ⁠ b ⁠, the number $b^{p}-b$ is an integer multiple of ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers are composite numbers which have the same property.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers are also called Fermat pseudoprimes or **absolute Fermat pseudoprimes**.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] A Carmichael number will pass a Fermat primality test to every base b relatively prime to the number, even though it is not actually prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] This makes tests based on Fermat's Little Theorem less effective than strong probable prime tests such as the Baillie–PSW primality test and the Miller–Rabin primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] However, no Carmichael number is either an Euler–Jacobi pseudoprime or a strong pseudoprime to every base relatively prime to it so, in theory, either an Euler or a strong probable prime test could prove that a Carmichael number is, in fact, composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] is a 131-digit prime. p is the smallest prime factor of ⁠ N ⁠, so this Carmichael number is also a (not necessarily strong) pseudoprime to all bases less than ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] As numbers become larger, Carmichael numbers become increasingly rare.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] For example, there are 20138200 Carmichael numbers between 1 and 1021 (approximately one in 50 trillion (5×1013) numbers).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] An alternative and equivalent definition of Carmichael numbers is given by **Korselt's criterion**.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] It follows from this theorem that all Carmichael numbers are odd, since any even composite number that is square-free (and hence has only one prime factor of two) will have at least one odd prime factor, and thus $p-1\mid n-1$ results in an even dividing an odd, a contradiction.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] (The oddness of Carmichael numbers also follows from the fact that $-1$ is a Fermat witness for any even composite number.) From the criterion it also follows that Carmichael numbers are cyclic.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Additionally, it follows that there are no Carmichael numbers with exactly two prime divisors.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The first seven Carmichael numbers, from 561 to 8911, were all found by the Czech mathematician Václav Šimerka in 1885 (thus preceding not just Carmichael but also Korselt, although Šimerka did not find anything like Korselt's criterion).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] His work, published in Czech scientific journal *Časopis pro pěstování matematiky a fysiky*, however, remained unnoticed.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Korselt was the first who observed the basic properties of Carmichael numbers, but he did not give any examples.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] That 561 is a Carmichael number can be seen with Korselt's criterion.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] In 1910, Carmichael himself also published the smallest such number, 561, and the numbers were later named after him.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Jack Chernick proved a theorem in 1939 which can be used to construct a subset of Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The number $(6k+1)(12k+1)(18k+1)$ is a Carmichael number if its three factors are all prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Whether this formula produces an infinite quantity of Carmichael numbers is an open question (though it is implied by Dickson's conjecture).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Paul Erdős heuristically argued there should be infinitely many Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] (Red) Alford, Andrew Granville and Carl Pomerance used a bound on Olson's constant to show that there really do exist infinitely many Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Specifically, they showed that for sufficiently large ⁠ n ⁠, there are at least $n^{2/7}$ Carmichael numbers between 1 and ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Thomas Wright proved that if a and m are relatively prime, then there are infinitely many Carmichael numbers in the arithmetic progression ⁠ $a+k\cdot m$ ⁠, where ⁠ $k=1,2,\ldots$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Löh and Niebuhr in 1992 found some very large Carmichael numbers, including one with 1101518 factors and over 16 million digits.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] This has been improved to 10333229505 prime factors and 295486761787 digits, so the largest known Carmichael number is much greater than the largest known prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers have at least three prime factors.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The second Carmichael number (1105) can be expressed as the sum of two squares in more ways than any smaller number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The third Carmichael number (1729) is the Hardy-Ramanujan Number: the smallest number that can be expressed as the sum of two cubes (of positive numbers) in two different ways.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Let $C(X)$ denote the number of Carmichael numbers less than or equal to ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] He further gave a heuristic argument suggesting that this upper bound should be close to the true growth rate of ⁠ $C(X)$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Regarding the asymptotic distribution of Carmichael numbers, there have been several conjectures.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] In 1956, Erdős conjectured that there were $X^{1-o(1)}$ Carmichael numbers for *X* sufficiently large.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers up to ⁠ X ⁠, where ⁠ $L(x)=\exp {\left({\frac {\log x\log \log \log x}{\log \log x}}\right)}$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] In 2021, Daniel Larsen proved an analogue of Bertrand's postulate for Carmichael numbers first conjectured by Alford, Granville, and Pomerance in 1994.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The notion of Carmichael number generalizes to a Carmichael ideal in any number field ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] When ⁠ K ⁠ is ⁠ $\mathbf {Q}$ ⁠, the ideal ${\mathfrak {a}}$ is principal, and if we let ⁠ a ⁠ be its positive generator then the ideal ${\mathfrak {a}}=(a)$ is Carmichael exactly when ⁠ a ⁠ is a Carmichael number in the usual sense.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] When ⁠ K ⁠ is larger than the rationals it is easy to write down Carmichael ideals in ⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ ⁠: for any prime number ⁠ p ⁠ that splits completely in ⁠ K ⁠, the principal ideal $p{\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is a Carmichael ideal.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Since infinitely many prime numbers split completely in any number field, there are infinitely many Carmichael ideals in ⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] For example, if ⁠ p ⁠ is any prime number that is 1 mod 4, the ideal ⁠ $(p)$ ⁠ in the Gaussian integers $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ is a Carmichael ideal.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] A positive composite integer n is a Lucas–Carmichael number if and only if n is square-free, and for all prime divisors p of ⁠ n ⁠, it is true that ⁠ $p+1\mid n+1$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Quasi–Carmichael numbers are squarefree composite numbers ⁠ n ⁠ with the property that for every prime factor ⁠ p ⁠ of ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $p+b$ ⁠ divides ⁠ $n+b$ ⁠ positively with ⁠ b ⁠ being any integer besides 0.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] If ⁠ $b=-1$ ⁠, these are Carmichael numbers, and if ⁠ $b=1$ ⁠, these are Lucas–Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] An *n*-**Knödel number** for a given positive integer *n* is a composite number *m* with the property that each ⁠ $i<m$ ⁠ coprime to *m* satisfies ⁠ $i^{m-n}\equiv 1{\pmod {m}}$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The ⁠ $n=1$ ⁠ case are Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers can be generalized using concepts of abstract algebra.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The above definition states that a composite integer *n* is Carmichael precisely when the *n*th-power-raising function *p**n* from the ring **Z***n* of integers modulo *n* to itself is the identity function.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The identity is the only **Z***n*-algebra endomorphism on **Z***n* so we can restate the definition as asking that *p**n* be an algebra endomorphism of **Z***n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] As above, *p**n* satisfies the same property whenever *n* is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] The *n*th-power-raising function *p**n* is also defined on any **Z***n*-algebra **A**.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] A theorem states that *n* is prime if and only if all such functions *p**n* are algebra endomorphisms.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] In-between these two conditions lies the definition of **Carmichael number of order m** for any positive integer *m* as any composite number *n* such that *p**n* is an endomorphism on every **Z***n*-algebra that can be generated as **Z***n*-module by *m* elements.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Carmichael numbers of order 1 are just the ordinary Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] Korselt's criterion can be generalized to higher-order Carmichael numbers, as shown by Howe.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] A heuristic argument, given in the same paper, appears to suggest that there are infinitely many Carmichael numbers of order *m*, for any *m*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/carmichael-number] However, not a single Carmichael number of order 3 or above is known.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] In number theory, **Fermat's little theorem** states that if p is a prime number, then for any integer a, the number *a**p* − *a* is an integer multiple of p.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is the basis for the Fermat primality test and is one of the fundamental results of elementary number theory.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] The theorem is named after Pierre de Fermat, who stated it in 1640.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] It is called the "little theorem" to distinguish it from Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Pierre de Fermat first stated the theorem in a letter dated October 18, 1640, to his friend and confidant Frénicle de Bessy.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Euler provided the first published proof in 1736, in a paper titled "Theorematum Quorundam ad Numeros Primos Spectantium Demonstratio" (in English: "Demonstration of Certain Theorems Concerning Prime Numbers") in the *Proceedings* of the St.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Petersburg Academy, but Leibniz had given virtually the same proof in an unpublished manuscript from sometime before 1683.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Albert's *Modern Higher Algebra* (1937), which refers to "the so-called 'little' Fermat theorem" on page 206.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Some mathematicians independently made the related hypothesis (sometimes incorrectly called the Chinese hypothesis) that 2*p* ≡ 2 (mod *p*) if and only if p is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Indeed, the "if" part is true, and it is a special case of Fermat's little theorem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] However, the "only if" part is false: For example, 2341 ≡ 2 (mod 341), but 341 = 11 × 31 is a pseudoprime to base 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Several proofs of Fermat's little theorem are known.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] It is frequently proved as a corollary of Euler's theorem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] where *φ*(*n*) denotes Euler's totient function (which counts the integers from 1 to n that are coprime to n).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is indeed a special case, because if n is a prime number, then *φ*(*n*) = *n* − 1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] A corollary of Euler's theorem is: For every positive integer n, if the integer a is coprime with n, then $x\equiv y{\pmod {\varphi (n)}}\quad {\text{implies}}\quad a^{x}\equiv a^{y}{\pmod {n}},$ for any integers x and y.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If n is prime, this is also a corollary of Fermat's little theorem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] This is widely used in modular arithmetic, because this allows reducing modular exponentiation with large exponents to exponents smaller than n.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Euler's theorem is used with n not prime in public-key cryptography, specifically in the RSA cryptosystem, typically in the following way: if $y=x^{e}{\pmod {n}},$ retrieving x from the values of y, e and n is easy if one knows *φ*(*n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] On the other hand, if *n* = *pq* is the product of two distinct prime numbers, then *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] In this case, finding f from n and e is as difficult as computing *φ*(*n*) (this has not been proven, but no algorithm is known for computing f without knowing *φ*(*n*)).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Knowing only n, the computation of *φ*(*n*) has essentially the same difficulty as the factorization of n, since *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1), and conversely, the factors p and q are the (integer) solutions of the equation *x*2 − (*n* − *φ*(*n*) + 1) *x* + *n* = 0.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] The basic idea of RSA cryptosystem is thus: If a message x is encrypted as *y* = *xe* (mod *n*), using public values of n and e, then, with the current knowledge, it cannot be decrypted without finding the (secret) factors p and q of n.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Fermat's little theorem is also related to the Carmichael function and Carmichael's theorem, as well as to Lagrange's theorem in group theory.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] The converse of Fermat's little theorem fails for Carmichael numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If there exists an integer a such that $a^{p-1}\equiv 1{\pmod {p}}$ and for all primes q dividing *p* − 1 one has $a^{(p-1)/q}\not \equiv 1{\pmod {p}},$ then p is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] This theorem forms the basis for the Lucas primality test, an important primality test, and Pratt's primality certificate.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If a and p are coprime numbers such that *a**p*−1 − 1 is divisible by p, then p need not be prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If it is not, then p is called a *(Fermat) pseudoprime* to base a.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] The first pseudoprime to base 2 was found in 1820 by Pierre Frédéric Sarrus: 341 = 11 × 31.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] A number p that is a Fermat pseudoprime to base a for every number a coprime to p is called a Carmichael number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Alternately, any number p satisfying the equality $\gcd \left(p,\sum _{a=1}^{p-1}a^{p-1}\right)=1$ is either a prime or a Carmichael number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] This result may be deduced from Fermat's little theorem by the fact that, if p is an odd prime, then the integers modulo p form a finite field, in which 1 modulo p has exactly two square roots, 1 and −1 modulo p.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Note that *a**d* ≡ 1 (mod *p*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ 1 (mod *p*), because the congruence relation is compatible with exponentiation.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] And *a**d* = *a*20*d* ≡ −1 (mod *p*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ −1 (mod *p*) since d is odd, for the same reason.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] That is why one usually chooses a random a in the interval 1 < *a* < *p* − 1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If *b* ≠ 1 and −1 has not been obtained by squaring, then p is a *composite* and a is a witness for the compositeness of p.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Otherwise, p is a *strong probable prime to base a*; that is, it may be prime or not.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] If p is composite, the probability that the test declares it a strong probable prime anyway is at most 1⁄4, in which case p is a *strong pseudoprime*, and a is a *strong liar*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Therefore after k non-conclusive random tests, the probability that p is composite is at most 4−*k*, and may thus be made as low as desired by increasing k.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] In summary, the test either proves that a number is composite or asserts that it is prime with a probability of error that may be chosen as low as desired.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] The test is very simple to implement and computationally more efficient than all known deterministic tests.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/fermat-s-little-theorem] Therefore, it is generally used before starting a proof of primality.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The **Miller–Rabin primality test** or **Rabin–Miller primality test** is a probabilistic primality test: an algorithm which determines whether a given number is likely to be prime, similar to the Fermat primality test and the Solovay–Strassen primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] It is of historical significance in the search for a polynomial-time deterministic primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Its probabilistic variant remains widely used in practice, as one of the simplest and fastest tests known.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Miller's version of the test is deterministic, but its correctness relies on the unproven extended Riemann hypothesis.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Rabin modified it to obtain an unconditional probabilistic algorithm in 1980.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Similarly to the Fermat and Solovay–Strassen tests, the Miller–Rabin primality test checks whether a specific property, which is known to hold for prime values, holds for the number under testing.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For a given odd integer $n>2$ , let’s write $n-1$ as $2^{s}d$ where s is a positive integer and d is an odd positive integer.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Let’s consider an integer a , called a *base*, which is coprime to n .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This simplifies to first checking for $a^{d}\equiv 1{\pmod {n}}$ and then $a^{2^{r}d}\equiv n-1{\pmod {n}}$ for successive values of r .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For each value of r , the value of the expression may be calculated using the value obtained for the previous value of r by squaring under the modulus of n .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence, by contraposition, if n is not a strong probable prime to base a , then n is definitely composite, and a is called a **witness** for the compositeness of n .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, this property is not an exact characterization of prime numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] If n is composite, it may nonetheless be a strong probable prime to base a , in which case it is called a **strong pseudoprime**, and a is a **strong liar**.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] No composite number is a strong pseudoprime to all bases at the same time (contrary to the Fermat primality test for which Fermat pseudoprimes to all bases exist: the Carmichael numbers).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However no simple way of finding a witness is known.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] A naïve solution is to try all possible bases, which yields an inefficient deterministic algorithm.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The Miller test is a more efficient variant of this (see section *Miller test* below).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Another solution is to pick a base at random.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] When *n* is composite, most bases are witnesses, so the test will detect *n* as composite with a reasonably high probability (see section *Accuracy* below).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] We can quickly reduce the probability of a false positive to an arbitrarily small rate, by combining the outcome of as many independently chosen bases as necessary to achieve the said rate.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] There seems to be diminishing returns in trying many bases, because if *n* is a pseudoprime to some base, then it seems more likely to be a pseudoprime to another base.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Note that *a**d* ≡ 1 (mod *n*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ 1 (mod *n*), because the congruence relation is compatible with exponentiation.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] And *a**d* = *a*20*d* ≡ −1 (mod *n*) holds trivially for *a* ≡ −1 (mod *n*) since d is odd, for the same reason.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] That is why random a are usually chosen in the interval 1 < *a* < *n* − 1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For testing arbitrarily large n, choosing bases at random is essential, as we don't know the distribution of witnesses and strong liars among the numbers 2, 3, ..., *n* − 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, a pre-selected set of a few small bases guarantees the identification of all composites up to a pre-computed maximum.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This maximum is generally quite large compared to the bases.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This gives very fast deterministic tests for small enough *n* (see section *Testing against small sets of bases* below).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Here is a proof that, if *n* is a prime, then the only square roots of 1 modulo *n* are 1 and −1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Certainly 1 and −1, when squared modulo *n*, always yield 1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] It remains to show that there are no other square roots of 1 modulo *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This is a special case, here applied with the polynomial X2 − 1 over the finite field **Z**/*n***Z**, of the more general fact that a polynomial over some field has no more roots than its degree (this theorem follows from the existence of an Euclidean division for polynomials).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Suppose that *x* is a square root of 1 modulo *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] In other words, *n* divides the product (*x* − 1)(*x* + 1).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] By Euclid's lemma, since *n* is prime, it divides one of the factors *x* − 1 or *x* + 1, implying that *x* is congruent to either 1 or −1 modulo *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Here is a proof that, if *n* is an odd prime, then it is a strong probable prime to base *a*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Since the first term is congruent to 1, the second term is a square root of 1 modulo *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] By the previous lemma, it is congruent to either 1 or −1 modulo *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Otherwise, it is congruent to 1 and we can iterate the reasoning.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] At the end, either one of the terms is congruent to −1, or all of them are congruent to 1, and in particular the last term, *a**d*, is.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Suppose we wish to determine if $n=221$ is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] We randomly select a number a such that $2\leq a\leq n-2$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Since $220\equiv -1{\text{ mod }}n$ , either 221 is prime, or 174 is a strong liar for 221.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence 137 is a witness for the compositeness of 221, and 174 was in fact a strong liar.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Note that this tells us nothing about the factors of 221 (which are 13 and 17).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, the example with 341 in a later section shows how these calculations can sometimes produce a factor of *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For a practical guide to choosing the value of *a*, see Testing against small sets of bases.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The algorithm can be written in pseudocode as follows.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The parameter *k* determines the accuracy of the test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The greater the number of rounds, the more accurate the result.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Using repeated squaring, the running time of this algorithm is O(*k* *n*3), for an *n*-digit number, and *k* is the number of rounds performed; thus this is an efficient, polynomial-time algorithm.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] FFT-based multiplication, for example the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm, can decrease the running time to O(*k* *n*2 log *n* log log *n*) = Õ(*k* *n*2).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The error made by the primality test is measured by the probability that a composite number is declared probably prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The more bases *a* are tried, the better the accuracy of the test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] It can be shown that if *n* is composite, then at most ⁠1/4⁠ of the bases *a* are strong liars for *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] As a consequence, if *n* is composite then running *k* iterations of the Miller–Rabin test will declare *n* probably prime with a probability at most 4−*k*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This is an improvement over the Solovay–Strassen test, whose worst‐case error bound is 2−*k*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Moreover, the Miller–Rabin test is strictly stronger than the Solovay–Strassen test in the sense that for every composite *n*, the set of strong liars for *n* is a subset of the set of Euler liars for *n*, and for many *n*, the subset is proper.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] In addition, for large values of *n*, the probability for a composite number to be declared probably prime is often significantly smaller than 4−*k*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For instance, for most numbers *n*, this probability is bounded by 8−*k*; the proportion of numbers *n* which invalidate this upper bound vanishes as we consider larger values of *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence the *average* case has a much better accuracy than 4−*k*, a fact which can be exploited for *generating* probable primes (see below).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, such improved error bounds should not be relied upon to *verify* primes whose probability distribution is not controlled, since a cryptographic adversary might send a carefully chosen pseudoprime in order to defeat the primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] In such contexts, only the *worst‐case* error bound of 4−*k* can be relied upon.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] We are often interested instead in the inverse conditional probability $\Pr(\lnot P\mid M\!R_{k})$ : the probability that a number which has been declared as a strong probable prime is in fact composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] In the last equation, we simplified the expression using the fact that all prime numbers are correctly reported as strong probable primes (the test has no false negative).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence this conditional probability is related not only to the error measure discussed above — which is bounded by 4−*k* — but also to the probability distribution of the input number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] In the general case, as said earlier, this distribution is controlled by a cryptographic adversary, thus unknown, so we cannot deduce much about $\Pr(\lnot P\mid M\!R_{k})$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, in the case when we use the Miller–Rabin test to *generate* primes (see below), the distribution is chosen by the generator itself, so we can exploit this result.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Caldwell points out that strong probable prime tests to different bases sometimes provide an additional primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Just as the strong test checks for the existence of more than two square roots of 1 modulo *n*, two such tests can sometimes check for the existence of more than two square roots of −1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Suppose that, in the course of our probable prime tests, we come across two bases *a* and *a′* for which $a^{2^{r}d}\equiv a^{\prime \,2^{r'}d}\equiv -1{\pmod {n}}$ with *r*, *r′* ≥ 1.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This means that we have computed two square roots as part of the testing, and can check whether $a^{2^{r-1}d}\equiv \pm a^{\prime \,2^{r'-1}d}{\pmod {n}}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This must always hold if *n* is prime; if not, we have found more than two square roots of −1 and proved that *n* is composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This is only possible if *n* ≡ 1 (mod 4), and we pass probable prime tests with two or more bases *a* such that *ad* ≢ ±1 (mod *n*), but it is an inexpensive addition to the basic Miller–Rabin test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The Miller–Rabin algorithm can be made deterministic by trying all possible values of *a* below a certain limit.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Taking *n* as the limit would imply O(*n*) trials, hence the running time would be exponential with respect to the size log *n* of the input.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] To improve the running time, the challenge is then to lower the limit as much as possible while keeping the test reliable.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Assuming the truth of the generalized Riemann hypothesis (which Miller, confusingly, calls the "extended Riemann hypothesis"), it is known that the group is generated by its elements smaller than O((ln *n*)2), which was already noted by Miller.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The constant involved in the Big O notation was reduced to 2 by Eric Bach.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The full power of the generalized Riemann hypothesis is not needed to ensure the correctness of the test: as we deal with subgroups of even index, it suffices to assume the validity of GRH for quadratic Dirichlet characters.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The running time of the algorithm is, in the soft-O notation, Õ((log *n*)4) (using FFT‐based multiplication).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The Miller test is not used in practice.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For most purposes, proper use of the probabilistic Miller–Rabin test or the Baillie–PSW primality test gives sufficient confidence while running much faster.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] It is also slower in practice than commonly used proof methods such as APR-CL and ECPP which give results that do not rely on unproven assumptions.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For theoretical purposes requiring a deterministic polynomial time algorithm, it was superseded by the AKS primality test, which also does not rely on unproven assumptions.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] When the number *n* to be tested is small, trying all *a* < 2(ln *n*)2 is not necessary, as much smaller sets of potential witnesses are known to suffice.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, proving this to hold for all integers up to the bound is substantially more difficult.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Other criteria of this sort, often more efficient (fewer bases required) than those shown above, exist by removing the requirement for the bases to be consecutive.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Further optimization by Steve Worley and others, involves partitioning the integers less than N into subsets and preselecting witnesses that correctly evaluate all elements of that subset.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] There is a small list of potential witnesses for every possible input size (at most *b* values for *b*‐bit numbers).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] However, no finite set of bases is sufficient for all composite numbers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Alford, Granville, and Pomerance have shown that there exist infinitely many composite numbers *n* whose smallest compositeness witness is at least (ln *n*)1/(3ln ln ln *n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] They also argue heuristically that the smallest number *w* such that every composite number below *n* has a compositeness witness less than *w* should be of order Θ(log *n* log log *n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] By inserting greatest common divisor calculations into the above algorithm, we can sometimes obtain a factor of *n* instead of merely determining that *n* is composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This occurs for example when *n* is a probable prime to base *a* but not a strong probable prime to base *a*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] From this we deduce that *A* = gcd(*x* − 1, *n*) and *B* = gcd(*x* + 1, *n*) are nontrivial (not necessarily prime) factors of *n* (in fact, since *n* is odd, these factors are coprime and *n* = *AB*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence, if factoring is a goal, these gcd calculations can be inserted into the algorithm at little additional computational cost.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This is *not* a probabilistic factorization algorithm because it is only able to find factors for numbers *n* which are pseudoprime to base *a* (in other words, for numbers *n* such that *a**n*−1 ≡ 1 mod *n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For other numbers, the algorithm only returns "composite" with no further information.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] For example, consider *n* = 341 and *a* = 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This tells us that *n* is a pseudoprime base 2, but not a strong pseudoprime base 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] By computing a gcd at this stage, we find a factor of 341: gcd(32 − 1, 341) = 31.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The same technique can be applied to the square roots of any other value, particularly the square roots of −1 mentioned in § Combining multiple tests.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The Miller–Rabin test can be used to generate strong probable primes, simply by drawing integers at random until one passes the test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This algorithm terminates almost surely (since at each iteration there is a chance to draw a prime number).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Of course the worst-case running time is infinite, since the outer loop may never terminate, but that happens with probability zero.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] As per the geometric distribution, the expected number of draws is ${\tfrac {1}{\Pr(M\!R_{k})}}$ (reusing notations from earlier).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] As any prime number passes the test, the probability of being prime gives a coarse lower bound to the probability of passing the test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Using an asymptotic expansion of π (an extension of the prime number theorem), we can approximate this probability when *b* grows towards infinity.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence we can expect the generator to run no more Miller–Rabin tests than a number proportional to *b*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Taking into account the worst-case complexity of each Miller–Rabin test (see earlier), the expected running time of the generator with inputs *b* and *k* is then bounded by O(*k* *b*4) (or Õ(*k* *b*3) using FFT-based multiplication).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] The error measure of this generator is the probability that it outputs a composite number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Hence, for large enough *b*, this error measure is less than ${\tfrac {\ln 2}{2}}4^{-k}b$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Using the fact that the Miller–Rabin test itself often has an error bound much smaller than 4−*k* (see earlier), Damgård, Landrock and Pomerance derived several error bounds for the generator, with various classes of parameters *b* and *k*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] These error bounds allow an implementor to choose a reasonable *k* for a desired accuracy.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] One of these error bounds is 4−*k*, which holds for all *b* ≥ 2 (the authors only showed it for *b* ≥ 51, while Ronald Burthe Jr. completed the proof with the remaining values 2 ≤ *b* ≤ 50).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] Again this simple bound can be improved for large values of *b*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/miller-rabin-primality-test] This bound is smaller than 4−*k* as soon as *b* ≥ 32.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] A **primality test** is an algorithm for determining whether an input number is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Among other fields of mathematics, it is used for cryptography.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Unlike integer factorization, primality tests do not generally give prime factors, only stating whether the input number is prime or not.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Factorization is thought to be a computationally difficult problem, whereas primality testing is comparatively easy (its running time is polynomial in the size of the input).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Some primality tests prove that a number is prime, while others like Miller–Rabin prove that a number is composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Therefore, the latter might more accurately be called *compositeness tests* instead of primality tests.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The simplest primality test is *trial division*: given an input number, n , check whether it is divisible by any prime number between 2 and ${\sqrt {n}}$ (i.e., whether the division leaves no remainder).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] All divisors $p\geq {\sqrt {n}}$ , must have a divisor ${\frac {n}{p}}\leq {\sqrt {n}}$ , and a prime divisor q of ${\frac {n}{p}}$ , and therefore looking for prime divisors at most ${\sqrt {n}}$ is sufficient.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] When all possible divisors up to n are tested, some divisors will be discovered *twice*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Products past $10\times 10$ are the reverse of products that appeared earlier.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] For example, $5\times 20$ and $20\times 5$ are the reverse of each other.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] This observation generalizes to all n : all divisor pairs of n contain a divisor less than or equal to ${\sqrt {n}}$ , so the algorithm need only search for divisors less than or equal to ${\sqrt {n}}$ to guarantee detection of all divisor pairs.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Also, 2 is a prime dividing 100, which immediately proves that 100 is not prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Every positive integer except 1 is divisible by at least one prime number by the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Therefore the algorithm need only search for *prime* divisors less than or equal to ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] For another example, consider how this algorithm determines the primality of 17.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Neither divides 17, proving that 17 is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Upon checking each, one discovers that ${\frac {221}{13}}=17$ , proving that 221 is not prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In cases where computing the list of primes $\leq {\sqrt {n}}$ is not feasible, all numbers between 2 and ${\sqrt {n}}$ can be simply (and slowly) checked for divisors.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] A simple improvement is to test divisibility by 2 and by just the odd numbers between 3 and ${\sqrt {n}}$ , since divisibility by an even number implies divisibility by 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Observe that all primes greater than 5 are of the form $6k+i$ for a nonnegative integer k and $i\in \{1,5\}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Indeed, every integer is of the form $6k+i$ for a positive integer k and $i\in \{0,1,2,3,4,5\}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Since 2 divides $6k,6k+2$ , and $6k+4$ , and 3 divides $6k$ and $6k+3$ , the only possible remainders mod 6 for a prime greater than 3 are 1 and 5.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] So, a more efficient primality test for n is to test whether n is divisible by 2 or 3, then to check through all numbers of the form $6k+1$ and $6k+5$ which are $\leq {\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] This is almost three times as fast as testing all numbers up to ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Generalizing further, all primes greater than $p_{m}$ (the m th prime number) are of the form $p_{m}\#\cdot k+i$ , where $\{k,i\in \mathbb {Z} \mid 0\leq i<p_{m}\#\land {\text{gcd}}\left(p_{m}\#,i\right)=1\}$ and $p_{m}\#$ is the primorial – the product of the first m primes.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] All integers are of the form $30k+i$ , where $\{k,i\in \mathbb {Z} \mid 0\leq i<30\}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Of course, not all numbers of the form $p_{m}\#\cdot k+i$ with i coprime to $p_{m}\#$ are prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] While $\lim _{m\to \infty }{\frac {\phi \left(p_{m}\#\right)}{p_{m}\#}}=0$ , where $\phi \left(m\right)$ is the Euler totient function, checking for divisibility by all primes that are less than $p_{m}\#$ is still needed.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Observations analogous to the preceding can be applied recursively, giving the Sieve of Eratosthenes.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] One way to speed up these methods (and all the others mentioned below) is to pre-compute and store a list of all primes up to a certain bound, such as all primes up to 200.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] (Such a list can be computed with the Sieve of Eratosthenes or by an algorithm that tests each incremental m against all known primes $\leq {\sqrt {m}}$ ).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Then, before testing n for primality with a large-scale method, n can first be checked for divisibility by any prime from the list.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] If it is divisible by any of those numbers then it is composite, and any further tests can be skipped.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Although this method requires about p modular multiplications, rendering it impractical, theorems about primes and modular residues form the basis of many more practical methods.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] These are tests that seem to work well in practice, but are unproven and therefore are not, technically speaking, algorithms at all.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Fermat primality test and the Fibonacci test are simple examples, and they are effective when combined.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] where *fk* is the *k*-th Fibonacci number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The first condition is the Fermat primality test using base 2.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Selfridge, Pomerance and Wagstaff together offered $620 for a counterexample or proof that there is none, with the prize now due from the Number Theory Foundation.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Probabilistic tests are more rigorous than heuristics in that they provide provable bounds on the probability of being fooled by a composite number.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Multiple popular primality tests are probabilistic tests.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] These tests use, apart from the tested number *n*, some other numbers *a* which are chosen at random from some sample space; the usual randomized primality tests never report a prime number as composite, but it is possible for a composite number to be reported as prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Check equality (corresponding to the chosen test) involving *a* and the given number *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] If the equality fails to hold true, then *n* is a composite number and *a* is a *witness* for the compositeness, and the test stops.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Get back to the step one until the required accuracy is reached.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] After one or more iterations, if *n* is not found to be a composite number, then it can be declared probably prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The simplest probabilistic primality test is the Fermat primality test (actually a compositeness test).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] If *an*−1 (modulo *n*) is 1 but *n* is not prime, then *n* is called a pseudoprime to base *a*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In practice, if *an*−1 (modulo *n*) is 1, then *n* is usually prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In fact, 341 is the smallest pseudoprime base 2 (see Figure 1 of ).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] There are only 21853 pseudoprimes base 2 that are less than 2.5×1010 (see page 1005 of ).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] This means that, for *n* up to 2.5×1010, if *2n*−1 (modulo *n*) equals 1, then *n* is prime, unless *n* is one of these 21853 pseudoprimes.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Some composite numbers (Carmichael numbers) have the property that *an* − 1 is 1 (modulo *n*) for every *a* that is coprime to *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Nevertheless, the Fermat test is often used if a rapid screening of numbers is needed, for instance in the key generation phase of the RSA public key cryptographic algorithm.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Miller–Rabin primality test and Solovay–Strassen primality test are more sophisticated variants, which detect all composites (once again, this means: for *every* composite number *n*, at least 3/4 (Miller–Rabin) or 1/2 (Solovay–Strassen) of numbers *a* are witnesses of compositeness of *n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Miller–Rabin primality test works as follows: Given an integer *n*, choose some positive integer *a* < *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] then *n* is composite and *a* is a witness for the compositeness.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Miller–Rabin test is a strong probable prime test (see PSW page 1004).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Solovay–Strassen test is an Euler probable prime test (see PSW page 1003).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] For each individual value of *a*, the Solovay–Strassen test is weaker than the Miller–Rabin test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] For example, if *n* = 1905 and *a* = 2, then the Miller-Rabin test shows that *n* is composite, but the Solovay–Strassen test does not.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] This is because 1905 is an Euler pseudoprime base 2 but not a strong pseudoprime base 2 (this is illustrated in Figure 1 of PSW).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Miller–Rabin and the Solovay–Strassen primality tests are simple and are much faster than other general primality tests.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] One method of improving efficiency further in some cases is the Frobenius pseudoprimality test; a round of this test takes about three times as long as a round of Miller–Rabin, but achieves a probability bound comparable to seven rounds of Miller–Rabin.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Frobenius test is a generalization of the Lucas probable prime test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Baillie–PSW primality test is a probabilistic primality test that combines a Fermat or Miller–Rabin test with a Lucas probable prime test to get a primality test that has no known counterexamples.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] That is, there are no known composite *n* for which this test reports that *n* is probably prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] It has been shown that there are no counterexamples for *n* $<2^{64}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Leonard Adleman and Ming-Deh Huang presented an errorless (but expected polynomial-time) variant of the elliptic curve primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Unlike the other probabilistic tests, this algorithm produces a primality certificate, and thus can be used to prove that a number is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The algorithm is prohibitively slow in practice.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] If quantum computers were available, primality could be tested asymptotically faster than by using classical computers.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] A combination of Shor's algorithm, an integer factorization method, with the Pocklington primality test could solve the problem in $O((\log n)^{3}(\log \log n)^{2}\log \log \log n)$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Near the beginning of the 20th century, it was shown that a corollary of Fermat's little theorem could be used to test for primality.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] This resulted in the Pocklington primality test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] However, as this test requires a partial factorization of *n* − 1 the running time was still quite slow in the worst case.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The first deterministic primality test significantly faster than the naive methods was the cyclotomy test; its runtime can be proven to be O((log *n*)*c* log log log *n*), where *n* is the number to test for primality and *c* is a constant independent of *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] A number of further improvements were made, but none could be proven to have polynomial running time.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] (Running time is measured in terms of the size of the input, which in this case is ~ log *n*, that being the number of bits needed to represent the number *n*.) The elliptic curve primality test can be proven to run in O((log *n*)6), if some conjectures on analytic number theory are true.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Similarly, under the generalized Riemann hypothesis (which Miller, confusingly, calls the "extended Riemann hypothesis"), the deterministic Miller's test, which forms the basis of the probabilistic Miller–Rabin test, can be proved to run in Õ((log *n*)4).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In practice, this algorithm is slower than the other two for sizes of numbers that can be dealt with at all.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Because the implementation of these two methods is rather difficult and creates a risk of programming errors, slower but simpler tests are often preferred.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In 2002, the first provably unconditional deterministic polynomial time test for primality was invented by Manindra Agrawal, Neeraj Kayal, and Nitin Saxena.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The AKS primality test runs in Õ((log *n*)12) (improved to Õ((log *n*)7.5) in the published revision of their paper), which can be further reduced to Õ((log *n*)6) if the Sophie Germain conjecture is true.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Subsequently, Lenstra and Pomerance presented a version of the test which runs in time Õ((log *n*)6) unconditionally.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Agrawal, Kayal and Saxena suggest a variant of their algorithm which would run in Õ((log *n*)3) if Agrawal's conjecture is true; however, a heuristic argument by Hendrik Lenstra and Carl Pomerance suggests that it is probably false.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] A modified version of the Agrawal's conjecture, the Agrawal–Popovych conjecture, may still be true.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In computational complexity theory, the formal language corresponding to the prime numbers is denoted as PRIMES.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] It is easy to show that PRIMES is in **Co-NP**: its complement COMPOSITES is in **NP** because one can decide compositeness by nondeterministically guessing a factor.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In 1975, Vaughan Pratt showed that there existed a certificate for primality that was checkable in polynomial time, and thus that PRIMES was in NP, and therefore in ⁠ ${\mathsf {NP\cap coNP}}$ ⁠.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The subsequent discovery of the Solovay–Strassen and Miller–Rabin algorithms put PRIMES in coRP.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] In 1992, the Adleman–Huang algorithm reduced the complexity to ⁠ ${\mathsf {{\color {Blue}ZPP}=RP\cap coRP}}$ ⁠, which superseded Pratt's result.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test from 1983 put PRIMES in **QP** (quasi-polynomial time), which is not known to be comparable with the classes mentioned above.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Because of its tractability in practice, polynomial-time algorithms assuming the Riemann hypothesis, and other similar evidence, it was long suspected but not proven that primality could be solved in polynomial time.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The existence of the AKS primality test finally settled this long-standing question and placed PRIMES in **P**.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] However, PRIMES is not known to be P-complete, and it is not known whether it lies in classes lying inside **P** such as NC or L.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] Certain number-theoretic methods exist for testing whether a number is prime, such as the Lucas test and Proth's test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] These tests typically require factorization of *n* + 1, *n* − 1, or a similar quantity, which means that they are not useful for general-purpose primality testing, but they are often quite powerful when the tested number *n* is known to have a special form.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] The Lucas test relies on the fact that the multiplicative order of a number *a* modulo *n* is *n* − 1 for a prime *n* when *a* is a primitive root modulo n.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/primality-test] If we can show *a* is primitive for *n*, we can show *n* is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The **Solovay–Strassen primality test**, developed by Robert M.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Solovay and Volker Strassen in 1977, is a probabilistic primality test to determine if a number is composite or probably prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The idea behind the test was discovered by M.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Artjuhov in 1967 (see Theorem E in the paper).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] This test has been largely superseded by the Baillie–PSW primality test and the Miller–Rabin primality test, but has great historical importance in showing the practical feasibility of the RSA cryptosystem.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] where $\left({\tfrac {a}{p}}\right)$ is the Legendre symbol.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The Jacobi symbol is a generalisation of the Legendre symbol to $\left({\tfrac {a}{n}}\right)$ , where *n* can be any odd integer.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The Jacobi symbol can be computed in time O((log *n*)²) using Jacobi's generalization of the law of quadratic reciprocity.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] holds for various values of the "base" *a*, given that *a* is relatively prime to *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] If *n* is prime then this congruence is true for all *a*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] So if we pick values of *a* at random and test the congruence, then as soon as we find an *a* which doesn't fit the congruence we know that *n* is not prime (but this does not tell us a nontrivial factorization of *n*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] This base *a* is called an *Euler witness* for *n*; it is a witness for the compositeness of *n*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The base *a* is called an *Euler liar* for *n* if the congruence is true while *n* is composite.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] are (Euler) witnesses as the set of Euler liars is a proper subgroup of $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} )^{*}$ .
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] This contrasts with the Fermat primality test, for which the proportion of witnesses may be much smaller.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Therefore, there are no (odd) composite *n* without many witnesses, unlike the case of Carmichael numbers for Fermat's test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Suppose we wish to determine if *n* = 221 is prime.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] We randomly select an *a* (greater than 1 and smaller than *n*): 47.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] This gives that, either 221 is prime, or 47 is an Euler liar for 221.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Hence 2 is an Euler witness for the compositeness of 221, and 47 was in fact an Euler liar.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Note that this tells us nothing about the prime factors of 221, which are actually 13 and 17.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Using fast algorithms for modular exponentiation, the running time of this algorithm is O(*k*·log3 *n*), where *k* is the number of different values of *a* that are tested.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] It is possible for the algorithm to return an incorrect answer.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] If the input ''n'' is indeed prime, then the output will always correctly be ''probably prime''.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] When *n* is odd and composite, at least half of all *a* with gcd(*a*,*n*) = 1 are Euler witnesses.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] We can prove this as follows: let {*a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**m*} be the Euler liars and *a* an Euler witness.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] This gives that each *a**i* gives a number *a*·*a**i*, which is also an Euler witness.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] So each Euler liar gives an Euler witness and so the number of Euler witnesses is larger or equal to the number of Euler liars.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Therefore, when *n* is composite, at least half of all *a* with gcd(*a*,*n*) = 1 is an Euler witness.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Hence, the probability of failure is at most 2−*k* (compare this with the probability of failure for the Miller–Rabin primality test, which is at most 4−*k*).
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] For purposes of cryptography the more bases *a* we test, i.e. if we pick a sufficiently large value of *k*, the better the accuracy of test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] Hence the chance of the algorithm failing in this way is so small that the (pseudo) prime is used in practice in cryptographic applications, but for applications for which it is important to have a prime, a test like ECPP or the Pocklington primality test should be used which *proves* primality.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The bound 1/2 on the error probability of a single round of the Solovay–Strassen test holds for any input *n*, but those numbers *n* for which the bound is (approximately) attained are extremely rare.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] for *k* rounds of the test, applied to uniformly random *n* ≤ *x*.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The same bound also applies to the related problem of what is the conditional probability of *n* being composite for a random number *n* ≤ *x* which has been declared prime in *k* rounds of the test.
[src:miller-rabin-primality/solovay-strassen-primality-test] The Solovay–Strassen algorithm shows that the decision problem **COMPOSITE** is in the complexity class **RP**.
